The Cambridge Society for Economic Pluralism's next event on the 4th of November is really exciting - they are interviewing sociologist Peter Andre about his paper “What’s Worth Knowing? Economists’ Opinions about Economics” with Armin Falk, interviewing 10,000 economists on their perceptions of the discipline. 

By asking the opinions of a wide and international range of economists, they were able to understand how researchers want economics to evolve. Join us to discuss policy relevance, specialization, multidisciplinary, riskiness, disruptiveness, and quality of research and get a glimpse of what economics may look like in the future. 

Free registration here: https://www.eventbrite.com.au/e/economists-opinions-about-economics-tickets-181624051427

December 17-23, 2021 is Socio-economic Planning and Development Week.

#Excerptionals: Investing in the Unseen: Cases on Biodiversity Conservation (Ateneo de Manila University Press, 2018) is a sourcebook on development management written by Benjamin C. Bagadion Jr. and edited by Violet B. Valdez. The book contains in-depth teaching cases that capture ground realities that illustrate the dilemmas of conservation along with the plight of protected area managers across different management modalities namely, local, national, and corporate settings.

The strategies and practices in the cases, both orthodox and unorthodox, can serve as a guide to effective management not only in environmental conservation, but in other fields as well.

Bagadion's book won Best Book in Science during the 38th National Book Awards in 2019.

Buy the book: http://www.ateneo.edu/ateneopress/product/investing-unseen-cases-biodiversity-conservation

Title:
Malaking karangalang maipakilala ang ating mga tagapagsalita para sa nalalapit na Ekonsepto event na pinamagatang KLIMANOMIKS: Our economic foot print and the climate change crisis webinar

Ang pangunahing mensahe ay manggagaling kay Attorney Paola Sherina A. Alvarez, ang kasalukuyang Assistant Secretary sa International  Finance and Special Projects at ang opisyal na Spokesperson at Head of Communications sa Department of Finance.

Kasunod nito, ating alamin kung ano nga ba ang Ecological Economics at paano ito nakatutulong sa pagkamit ng mga layuning pangkapaligiran? Halina't tuklasin ito at pakinggan ang ating tagapagsalita na Ms. Birte Strunk. Siya ay isang PhD student ng Economics sa New School for Social Research sa New York City. Nakatuon ang kaniyang pananaliksik sa Philosophy of Economics at Ecological Economics. Siya rin ay miyembro ng Post-Growth Economics Network at isang research fellow sa isang Germany-based ZOE Institute for future-fit economies. Kaengga-engganyong pakinggan!

Para sa ating susunod na talakayan, ibabahagi sa atin ni Dr. Gay Defiesta ang ugnayan ng ekonomiks at ang pabago-bagong klima.  ay isang Professor sa Ekonomiks na nagmula sa University of the Philippines Visayas. Siya ay may hawak na PhD sa Agricultural Economics na may pagpapakadalubhasa sa Natural Resources Economics and Environmental Science mula sa University of the Philippines Los Baños. Ang kaniyang mga pananaliksik ay nakatuon sa fisheries socioeconomic analysis, economic valuation of environmental resources, at climate change adaptation and vulnerability. Tunay na eksperto sa kaniyang larangan!

Ang pinakahuling talakayan ay tungkol sa mga oportunidad at mga hamon sa panahon ng COVID-19 pandemic at krisis sa klima. Mula sa Philippine branch ng The Climate Reality Project, ating abangan at subaybayan si Ginang Nazrin Camille Castro! Tinataglay ni Ginang Castro ang kadaubhasaan sa politikal at teknikal na aspeto sa pagpapaunlad ng mga polisiyang may kaugnayan sa klima. Nagsisilbi rin siya bilang Support Program Fellow ng mga climate vulnerable na mga bansa. Isang tunay na dalubhasa!

Abangan ang talakayan nina Ms. Birte Strunk, Dr. Gay Defiesta, at Ginang Nazrin Camille Castro ngayong ika-11 ng Disyembre mula 6:00 PM - 7:30 PM. 🕕

So, what happens next?
Zooming into the life after COVID-19 pandemic! Through the lens, join us in Magnify 2021!
Tackling several perspectives on healthcare, education, labor, and commerce, this webinar aims to enlighten and share the events with the occurrence of the pandemic and what comes after. Then, to see how the country copes with the changes brought by the COVID-19 Pandemic, with the Philippine economy and its aftermath, there are questions to answer, and it's time that we unpack and see these.
Look through the lens with us via Zoom Video Conference on Dec 6 and 7, 2021 (Monday and Tuesday) from 1:00 PM to 6:00 PM.
Registration will be open until December 3, 2021 and we only have limited slots left! So what are you waiting for? Register now!

The COVID-19 Pandemic had made a massive impact on everyone around the globe, with economic productivity put on hold in many industries of a country, where only the essentials move, where do we stand now? How has our country coped with the struggles that this virus had caused?
In the past year, the National Collegiate Economic Convention has delivered to not just the students but to the public the well deserved awareness about topics that matter to everyone in our country. It has been customary to provide more avenues of engagement in paving the way for further discussions about current issues. This year the National Collegiate Economics Convention will provide another platform to discuss the economic point of view of the aftermath of the Pandemic in the Philippines. So Magnify with us! 𝗘ndless 𝗖areer 𝗢pportunities 𝗡ow awaits 𝗘𝗖𝗢𝗡 students. There is no doubt that an economics degree will boost your employability in many areas, regardless of the industry you work in. The career paths in econ are so wide and diverse that for many Econ students, it can be overwhelming and frustrating which path to explore. Is it true that passion and work can go hand-in-hand? What should I expect after graduation? What’s the best career opportunity waiting for me out there?
It’s indeed the most wonderful time of the year for our Econ students! In its 39th year, UP Association of Economics Students proudly presents this year UP AES Econ Week. This year, we aim to answer your questions and deliver a career symposium, entitled 𝗙𝗜𝗚𝗨𝗥𝗘 𝗜𝗧 𝗢𝗨𝗧: 𝗔 𝗖𝗮𝗿𝗲𝗲𝗿 𝗣𝗮𝘁𝗵 𝗢𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗘𝗰𝗼𝗻𝗼𝗺𝗶𝗰𝘀 𝗦𝘁𝘂𝗱𝗲𝗻𝘁𝘀, to help and guide our econ students on which career path to take after college. We will hear from our guest speakers who will give us their valuable insights.

The Cambridge Society for Economic Pluralism's next event is on Wednesday 17th November, 5:30pm. The event will be online and as always the registration is free: https://central-banking-and-private-finance.eventbrite.com.au

Details about the event:
The success of 'independent' central banks in avoiding inflation is a crowning achievement of the macroeconomic policy consensus over the past four decades. Yet the swelling of balance sheets, the resurgence of inflationary pressures, and the looming threat of climate catastrophe all demand we interrogate the deeply political considerations that animate central bank policy. In particular, understanding the relationship between central banking and private finance is essential to examining these institutions' current operations and projecting directions for reform.
Dr. Benjamin Braun will be discussing his paper (summarised in this FT article) on the infrastructural power of CBs as it pertains to the resuscitation of market-based finance following the global financial crisis, highlighting the ways in which financial interests have shaped central banking policy. To quote at length from his article: "Financial markets, especially repo and securitisation markets, have come to serve as the infrastructure for monetary policy. The result has been a problematic alignment between the interests of bankers and central bankers, whereby both sides have a preference for a deep and liquid markets for … everything, ideally"
Professor Daniela Gabor will then be speaking on how the politico-financial nexus may compromise a holistic approach to a green transition, examining the role of central banks in the fiscal monetary architecture of the 'Wall Street Consensus', whereby: " development becomes a strategy of green financialization through which private finance manages the environmental crisis..." To listen to Professor Gabor discuss these issues, we highly recommend her appearance on the Odd Lots podcast
Following speaker presentations, there will be ample time for questions from the audience, so do come prepared!
